### What is AsyncPipe?

`AsyncPipe` automatically subscribes to an Observable or Promise in the template and returns the latest emitted value. It also handles **unsubscription** when the component is destroyed, preventing memory leaks.

### Basic Usage with Observables

```typescript
import { Observable, interval, map } from 'rxjs';

@Component({
  selector: 'app-clock',
  template: `
    <p>Current time: {{ time$ | async | date:'mediumTime' }}</p>
  `,
  standalone: true,
  imports: [AsyncPipe, DatePipe]
})
export class ClockComponent {
  time$: Observable<Date> = interval(1000).pipe(
    map(() => new Date())
  );
}
```

### Usage with Promises

```typescript
@Component({
  template: `
    <div>Data: {{ dataPromise | async }}</div>
  `
})
export class PromiseComponent {
  dataPromise: Promise<string> = Promise.resolve('Hello from Promise');
}
```

### Combining with *ngIf — The "as" Syntax

A common pattern is to use `*ngIf` with `as` to bind the emitted value to a template variable:

```typescript
@Component({
  template: `
    <div *ngIf="users$ | async as users; else loading">
      <p *ngFor="let user of users">{{ user.name }}</p>
    </div>
    <ng-template #loading>
      <p>Loading users...</p>
    </ng-template>
  `
})
export class UsersComponent {
  users$ = this.userService.getUsers();

  constructor(private userService: UserService) {}
}
```

This pattern handles:
1. **Loading state** — The `else` template shows while waiting for data.
2. **Null safety** — The `as` variable is only bound to when data arrives.
3. **Automatic unsubscription** — No manual cleanup needed.

### Benefits of AsyncPipe

| Benefit | Description |
|---------|-------------|
| Automatic subscription | No explicit `.subscribe()` calls in the component |
| Automatic unsubscription | Prevents memory leaks when component is destroyed |
| OnPush change detection | AsyncPipe triggers change detection only when a new value is emitted |
| Cleaner code | Reduces boilerplate in component classes |

### Multiple Observables

```html
<div *ngIf="{
  users: users$ | async,
  posts: posts$ | async
} as data">
  <p>Users: {{ data.users?.length }}</p>
  <p>Posts: {{ data.posts?.length }}</p>
</div>
```

### Manual Subscription vs AsyncPipe

**Without AsyncPipe (error-prone):**
```typescript
ngOnInit() {
  this.userService.getUsers().subscribe(users => {
    this.users = users;
  });
}

ngOnDestroy() {
  this.subscription?.unsubscribe(); // Easy to forget
}
```

**With AsyncPipe (clean):**
```typescript
// No subscription, no unsubscription, no stored state
template: `<div *ngIf="users$ | async as users">...</div>`
```

codeExample:
@Component({
  template: `
    <ul>
      <li *ngFor="let user of users$ | async">{{ user.name }}</li>
    </ul>
    <div *ngIf="userDetail$ | async as detail">
      {{ detail.name }} - {{ detail.email }}
    </div>
  `,
  imports: [AsyncPipe, NgFor, NgIf],
  standalone: true
})
export class UserComponent {
  users$ = this.userService.getUsers();
  userDetail$ = this.userService.getUserDetail(1);
  constructor(private userService: UserService) {}
}
